Maintenance Agreement between AEP Oklahoma Transmission Company, Inc. and Seven Cowboy Wind Project, LLC
Tariff Submitter: AEP Oklahoma Transmission Company, Inc. FERC Tariff Program Name: FERC FPA Electric Tariff Tariff Title: RS and SA Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: 11/3/2022 Description: SA#879 Tariff Record Title: AEPOTC-Seven Cowboy Wind Maintenance Agreement Option Code: A MAINTENANCE AGREEMENT
This Maintenance Agreement (the Agreement) is entered into as of November 7, 2022 (the Execution Date) between Seven Cowboy Wind Project, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Seven Cowboy) and AEP Oklahoma Transmission Company, Inc., an Oklahoma corporation (AEPOTC). For purposes of this Agreement, AEPOTC and Seven Cowboy shall each be referred to as a Party and collectively as the Parties.
RECITALS
A. Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP), Seven Cowboy, and AEPOTC are parties to that certain Amended and Restated Generator Interconnection Agreement, GEN-2016-037, First Revised Service Agreement No. 3923, filed with FERC on August 11, 2022, in Docket No. ER22-2633-000 with a requested effective date of August 8, 2022 (GIA). B. Pursuant to the GIA, Generator elected the option to construct certain Transmission Owner Interconnection Facilities and Stand Alone Network Upgrades described in Section 1(b) and Section 2(a) of Appendix A of the GIA (collectively, the Station). C. Contemporaneous with the execution of this Agreement, Seven Cowboy is transferring operational control of the Station to SPP and AEPOTC. Seven Cowboy and AEPOTC intend to have Seven Cowboy transfer ownership of the Station to AEPOTC. D. Seven Cowboy desires to have AEPOTC perform certain maintenance activities for the Station until the closing of transfer of ownership of the Station from Seven Cowboy to AEPOTC (Closing), and AEPOTC is willing to perform such maintenance activities upon the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement.
AGREEMENTS
NOW, THEREFORE, the Parties hereby agree as follows:
1. DEFINITIONS; RULES OF CONSTRUCTION 1.1. Definitions. As used in this Agreement, terms defined in Exhibit A have the meanings set forth therein. 1.2. Rules of Construction. Unless the context of this Agreement requires otherwise, the plural includes the singular, and the singular includes the plural. The words include, includes and including are not limiting and have the inclusive meaning of including without limitation. The words hereof, herein, hereby, hereunder and other similar terms of this Agreement refer to this Agreement as a whole and not exclusively to any particular provision of this Agreement. All pronouns and any variations thereof will be deemed to refer to masculine, feminine, or neuter, singular, or plural, as the identity of the Person or Persons may require. Unless otherwise expressly provided, any agreement, instrument, or Applicable Law defined or referred to herein means such agreement or instrument or Applicable Law as from time to time amended,
modified, or supplemented, including (in the case of agreements or instruments) by waiver or consent and (in the case of Applicable Law) by succession of comparable successor law and includes (in the case of agreements or instruments) references to all attachments thereto and instruments incorporated therein. A reference to a Party includes its successors and permitted assigns. This Agreement is the result of negotiations between, and has been reviewed by, the Parties, and their respective counsel have had the opportunity to review this Agreement. Accordingly, this Agreement will be deemed to be the product of all Parties hereto, and no ambiguity will be construed in favor of or against any Party. 2. TERM AND TERMINATION 2.1. Effective Date. AEPOTC shall file this Agreement with FERC and Seven Cowboy agrees to cooperate with AEPOTC and provide reasonable assistance to AEPOTC in such filing and proceedings related thereto. This Agreement shall become effective on the date deemed effective by FERC (Effective Date). However, if FERC or any reviewing court, in such order or in any separate order, suspends this Agreement or any part thereof , institutes an investigation or proceeding under the provisions of the Federal Power Act with respect to the justness and reasonableness of the provisions of this Agreement or any other agreement referred to or contemplated by this Agreement, or imposes any conditions, limitation or qualifications under any of the provisions of the Federal Power Act which individually or in the aggregate are determined by AEP or BBB to be adverse to it, then either AEP or BBB may terminate this Agreement upon written notice to the other Party. Alternatively, the Parties can agree that this Agreement should remain in ef f ect, with each Party retaining its rights to address any relevant order, including seeking to negotiate with the other Party an amendment to this Agreement. 2.2. Term. Subject to termination pursuant to Section 2.3, the term of this Agreement shall commence as of the Effective Date and shall continue until the Closing (Term). 2.3. Events of Termination. This Agreement may be terminated by the Parties as follows: 2.3.1. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for an Event of Default as provided in Section 5.2. 2.3.2. This Agreement may be terminated by mutual written agreement of the Parties. 2.4. Regulatory Approval of Termination. No termination hereunder shall become effective until the terminating Party (or the Parties jointly) tenders to FERC any required notification of termination of this Agreement and obtains acceptance thereof by FERC
as may be required. The FERC order accepting such termination will establish the effective date of the termination of this Agreement. 3. SERVICES 3.1. Services. 3.1.1. General Scope. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, AEPOTC will perform routine inspections of the Station facilities; on-site switching and tagging; preventive equipment maintenance; repair and replace worn or def ective f acilities as reasonably determined necessary by AEPOTC; subject to Section 3.1.2; perform vegetation control on the Station premises inside the Station fence; and such other maintenance activities as AEPOTC deems reasonably necessary and appropriate, subject to the limitations set forth in this Section 3.1 (the Services). AEPOTC shall provide the personnel, tools and equipment that AEPOTC deems necessary or advisable in connection with the Services. AEPOTC shall perform the routine inspection and preventive equipment maintenance activities at such f requency and using such practices as it would utilize f or similar maintenance activities for similar AEPOTC facilities. 3.1.2. Major Repairs or Replacement; Removal. If AEPOTC determines that a repair or replacement will exceed $10,000.00, AEPOTC will notify Seven Cowboy and will not perform such Service unless mutually agreed by AEPOTC and Seven Cowboy, except in the case of an Emergency (as defined in Section 3.1.4). Unless otherwise mutually agreed by the Parties, Seven Cowboy shall procure any necessary materials and equipment for major repairs or replacement. If Seven Cowboy does not provide its agreement for AEPOTC to undertake such repair or replacement, AEPOTC shall not have any liability under this Agreement, and shall be indemnified by Seven Cowboy pursuant to Article 9 for all damages arising out of or in connection with the f ailure to undertake such repair or replacement. Only Seven Cowboy may determine whether any of the Station f acilities may be retired, and except in an Emergency, AEPOTC shall not remove any Station facilities without the prior written approval of Seven Cowboy. 3.1.3. Warranties. To the extent practical, AEPOTC shall notify Seven Cowboy prior to repair or replacement of defective equipment such that Seven Cowboy may pursue warranties from its contractors and subcontractors. 3.1.4. Emergencies. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, if AEPOTC believes in good faith that a condition or circumstance that threatens imminent harm to Persons, property, the environment or the electric system exists or has occurred or that the performance of any of the Services would (in the reasonable judgment of AEPOTC) create an unreasonable safety risk to Persons, property or the environment, or would violate the safety and reliability policies or procedures of AEPOTC or any AEPOTC Resources (each of the f oregoing, an Emergency), AEPOTC may take such actions, or will cause such actions to be taken, that in AEPOTCs sole
judgment, are reasonably required to avoid or mitigate the Emergency without the need for prior notice to or approval by Seven Cowboy. If AEPOTC fails to take action, or to cause action to be taken, in response to an Emergency, Seven Cowboy may, upon notice to AEPOTC, take action, or cause action to be taken, to address the Emergency. 3.1.5. Scope Limitation. Seven Cowboy agrees that the following activities are not covered within the scope of the Services: (a) maintenance of Seven Cowboys generation facilities, including relays; (b) maintenance of the transmission line from the generation facility to the Point of Interconnection, including the fiber on that portion of the line; (c) capital improvements on the Station (as opposed to repair or replacement of equipment); (d) maintenance of grounds (including vegetation management) outside the Station fence; (e) compliance with, or performance under, Storm Water Pollution Prevention Plans; and (f) identification, reporting, spill response, or other compliance obligations associated with hazardous substances under any applicable environmental permit or otherwise. 3.1.6. Changes to Scope. The Parties may amend the scope of the Services pursuant to an amendment of this Agreement under Section 11.3. 3.2. Standards of Performance. AEPOTC shall perform the Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Law. 3.3. Use of Resources. AEPOTC may perform the Services under this Agreement by using subcontractors, suppliers, and consultants, and personnel from its Affiliates (collectively, the AEPOTC Resources). AEPOTC will be solely responsible for the supervision, direction, and control of all of the AEPOTC Resources engaged in the performance of the Services and such personnel will be employees or independent contractors of AEPOTC and not of Seven Cowboy. AEPOTC will have the right to remove, reassign, or take any other employment-related action regarding any of the AEPOTC Resources. AEPOTC shall cause each AEPOTC Resource performing the Services under this Agreement to comply with the terms and conditions of this Agreement, but only AEPOTC shall be liable under this Agreement f or the perf ormance of the obligations under this Agreement regardless of AEPOTCs reliance on AEPOTC Resources.
3.4. Access. Seven Cowboy grants AEPOTC and the AEPOTC Resources access rights to the Station at all times during the Term as may be reasonably necessary or convenient to AEPOTC to perform the Services. 3.5. Owner Instructions. At any time, AEPOTC may, if it reasonably deems it to be reasonably necessary or appropriate, request and receive detailed instructions (or clarifications of directives) from Seven Cowboy prior to taking any action with respect to the Services. AEPOTC may defer action pending the receipt of such written instructions. Seven Cowboy agrees that it will not unreasonably withhold or delay any instruction or direction to AEPOTC that is necessary to enable AEPOTC to provide the Services. 3.6. Compliance with Reliability Standards. AEPOTC will be responsible for the maintenance of the Station, including performing all tasks and preparing and retaining all records/documentation required to comply with applicable Reliability Standards. Seven Cowboy accepts that the Station will be maintained by AEPOTC in accordance with the AEPOTC maintenance and compliance practices applicable to similar f acilities. AEPOTC shall not be required to register as transmission owner, transmission operator, transmission planner, or any other applicable function with respect to the Station. AEPOTC is not required to make any filings with NERC or any other Governmental Authority on behalf of Seven Cowboy with respect to the Station, but AEPOTC shall provide Seven Cowboy, at Seven Cowboys expense, such records, information and documents reasonably necessary for Seven Cowboy to demonstrate compliance with applicable Reliability Standards in connection with the Station and the Services. 3.7. Responsibility for Non-Compliance. AEPOTC shall be responsible for any penalty or fine associated with non-compliance with the applicable Reliability Standards imposed as a result of a self-report, or a Governmental Authority audit, investigation, or proceeding related to the Station or the Services, to the extent caused by AEPOTCs gross negligence or willful misconduct in the performance of the Services. For the avoidance of doubt, any penalty or fine associated with non-compliance with any applicable Reliability Standards imposed as a result of a self-report, or a Governmental Authority audit, investigation, or proceeding related to the Station or the Services not caused by AEPOTCs gross negligence or willful misconduct shall not be AEPOTCs responsibility. 4. COSTS; INVOICING; TAXES 4.1. Responsibility for Costs. 4.1.1. Seven Cowboy agrees to reimburse AEPOTC for its costs to perform the Services. AEPOTCs costs f or the Services under this Agreement will include all costs, charges, and expenses reasonably incurred by AEPOTC in connection with the Services, including the costs of materials, equipment, and supplies from third parties, the costs of materials and equipment withdrawn from AEPOTCs internal inventories (or those of its Affiliates), transportation and storage costs, internal payroll and payroll loading factors, travel expenses, overhead factors, other internal costs, the costs to acquire
land rights, third party expenses, sales and use taxes, and fees and costs for Governmental Approvals. AEPOTCs costs shall be determined in a manner consistent with the formula set forth in Exhibit B. 4.1.2. Without limiting any rights it may have against third parties, Seven Cowboy will be responsible for all capital costs associated with the Station, including replacement of failed major components. 4.1.3. All costs reasonably incurred for all actions taken by AEPOTC to avoid or mitigate an Emergency in accordance with Section 3.1.4 will be paid or reimbursed by Seven Cowboy. 4.2. Information Concerning Costs. On reasonable advance written notice, Seven Cowboy will have the right to examine the pertinent records of AEPOTC as reasonably necessary to verify that costs invoiced pursuant to this Agreement were incurred in accordance with this Agreement. Any such examination will be conducted during regular business hours at the AEPOTC offices and shall be conducted in a manner that does not unreasonably interfere with AEPOTCs business or operations. Seven Cowboy will not have the right to examine the records pertaining to an invoice unless written notice of the examination is given within 24 months of the date of such invoice. AEPOTC shall not be obligated to provide Seven Cowboy with access or any other rights to inf ormation to the extent such information is: (a) otherwise restricted from disclosure by AEPOTC, or (b) privileged (e.g., pursuant to attorney-client privilege or work-product protection). Information obtained by Seven Cowboy from AEPOTC pursuant to this Section will be considered AEPOTCs Confidential Information pursuant to Article 10 regardless of whether such information is identified as confidential. 4.3. Invoices. 4.3.1. Not later than thirty (30) Calendar Days after the end of each month, AEPOTC will deliver to Seven Cowboy a monthly invoice which will show the charges payable by Seven Cowboy for the month and payment will be made by Seven Cowboy no later than thirty (30) Calendar Days after the date the invoice is received by Seven Cowboy. 4.3.2. If Seven Cowboy disputes any portion of any amount specified in an invoice delivered by AEPOTC, Seven Cowboy will pay the total amount of the invoice when due, and Seven Cowboy shall identify the disputed amount and state the basis for disputing part of the invoice amount. If it is determined that an overpayment or underpayment has been made by Seven Cowboy or the amount charged on an invoice is incorrect, then (a) in the case of any overpayment by Seven Cowboy, AEPOTC will promptly return the amount of the overpayment (or credit the amount of the overpayment on the next invoice) to Seven Cowboy, or (b) in the case of an underpayment by Seven Cowboy, Seven Cowboy will promptly pay the amount of the underpayment to AEPOTC. In each case, payment will be made together with interest at the Default Rate for the period from the date of overpayment or underpayment, until such amount has been paid or credited against a future invoice.
4.4. Tax Treatment of Costs. The amounts Seven Cowboy agrees to pay AEPOTC pursuant to Section 4.1 of this Agreement are exclusive of any state or local sales or use tax, or any other tax or similar charge. If AEPOTC is required by Applicable Law to pay or collect any such tax, or if Seven Cowboy is required to withhold such tax, then such amount will be paid or reimbursed to AEPOTC by Seven Cowboy. Seven Cowboy shall not be responsible to pay any f ederal, state or local tax imposed on AEPOTC and related to AEPOTCs receipt of monies under this Agreement. 5. DEFAULT; REMEDIES 5.1. Events of Default. An Event of Default will exist: 5.1.1. As to Seven Cowboy, upon Seven Cowboys failure to promptly pay any amount due under this Agreement within ten (10) Calendar Days following written notice of delinquency describing such failure in reasonable detail; or 5.1.2. As to a Party, if that Party fails to commence the cure of its breach of any other obligation under this Agreement within thirty (30) Calendar Days following written notification of such breach in reasonable detail; provided that if such failure is not capable of being cured within such thirty (30) Calendar Day period despite diligent efforts, then such thirty (30) Calendar Day period will be extended for such period as may be reasonably necessary to complete such cure with diligent efforts if the defaulting Party commences its cure within the initial thirty (30) Calendar Day period and thereafter prosecutes its cure diligently to completion. 5.1.3. A Party files a voluntary petition of bankruptcy or is adjudged bankrupt or insolvent, or has entered against it an order for relief, in any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding. 5.2. Termination. If an Event of Default occurs as to a Party described in Sections 5.1.1 or 5.1.2, then the other Party will have the right to terminate the Services by written notice to the defaulting Party. Upon an Event of Default by a Party described in Section 5.1.3, the other Party may terminate this Agreement by written notice to the defaulting Party, subject to Section 2.4. 5.3. Other remedies. 5.3.1. If an Event of Default occurs and while it persists with respect to a Party, the other Party may suspend performance of its obligations with respect to the Services under this Agreement (other than its obligations to pay money for Services provided) without prejudice to any other remedy that it may have under this Agreement or Applicable Law. 5.3.2. Whether or not a Party suspends performance of its obligations under, or terminates, this Agreement as a result of an Event of Default, Seven Cowboy will pay all amounts due, if any, for Services provided and indemnification under Article 9.
5.3.3. Subject to the limitations in Article 8 and the indemnification obligations of Section 9.1.3: (a) Seven Cowboy will be entitled to recover direct contract damages from AEPOTC as a result of an Event of Default (Allowable Damages); and (b) except as provided in this Section 5.3.3, the only other remedy for an Event of Default by AEPOTC is termination pursuant to Section 5.2. 6. FORCE MAJEURE 6.1. Effect of Force Majeure. In the event that any Party is rendered unable by reason of an event of Force Majeure occurring or arising without the fault or negligence of such Party, to perform, wholly or in part, any obligation or commitment set forth in this Agreement, then the obligations of such Party (except for the obligation to pay sums of money owing hereunder for periods prior to the event of Force Majeure) shall be suspended to the extent of such Force Majeure condition, and such Party shall not be deemed to be in default of this Agreement, for the period of such Force Majeure condition. The non-performing Party shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to rectify the conditions brought about by the Force Majeure and to avoid or minimize delay. 6.2. Notification. In the event of the occurrence of an event of Force Majeure which prevents a Party from performing its obligations hereunder, the affected Party shall promptly notify the other Party of such Force Majeure after the determination that event of Force Majeure has occurred. 6.3. Labor Disputes. Neither Party will be required by this Agreement to settle any strike, walkout, lockout, or other labor dispute on terms which, in the sole judgment of the Party involved in the dispute, are contrary to its interest, it being understood that the settlement of strikes, walkouts, lockouts, or other labor disputes will be at the sole discretion of the Party having the difficulty. 7. DISCLAIMER OF WARRANTIES SUBJECT TO SECTION 3.7 AND ARTICLE 9, THE REMEDIES CONTAINED IN ARTICLE 5 ARE SEVEN COWBOYS EXCLUSIVE REMEDIES, AND THEY ARE GIVEN AND ACCEPTED IN LIEU OF (A) ANY EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES BY AEPOTC, INCLUDING WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR GOOD AND WORKMANLIKE PERFORMANCE, AND (B) ANY OBLIGATION, LIABILITY, RIGHT, CLAIM OR REMEDY AT LAW OR IN EQUITY ARISING OUT OF ANY DEFECT IN THE SERVICES WHETHER SUCH CLAIM ARISES UNDER CONTRACT, TORT, STRICT LIABILITY, STATUTE OR ANY OTHER LEGAL OR EQUITABLE THEORY OR PRINCIPLE INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE, GROSS NEGLIGENCE, OR WILLFUL MISCONDUCT.
8. LIMITATION OF AEPOTCS LIABILITY; EXCLUSION OF CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES 8.1. Limitation of AEPOTCs Liability. Except for AEPOTCs indemnification obligations set forth in Article 9, AEPOTCs aggregate liability for all Allowable Damages, if any, for breach of its obligations under this Agreement related to Services will not exceed the amount billed by AEPOTC for the Services rendered during the Term of this Agreement. 8.2. Exclusion of Consequential Damages. Except as set forth in Article 9, neither Party will be liable under this Agreement for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, punitive, or exemplary damages in any action arising out of this Agreement, whether based on contract, tort, or any other theory of liability. 9. INDEMNIFICATION 9.1. Indemnification for Third-Party Claims. 9.1.1. Seven Cowboy shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless AEPOTC, its Affiliates, and the directors, managers, officers, employees, agents and AEPOTC Resources of AEPOTC and its Affiliates (each an AEPOTC Indemnified Person) for any personal injuries suffered by third parties or damage to a third partys tangible property, including reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense, and costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the AEPOTC Indemnif ied Person, arising in connection with this Agreement, and to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the negligence, gross negligence or willful misconduct of Seven Cowboy or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.1.2. Seven Cowboy shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless AEPOTC Indemnified Persons against penalties by any Governmental Authority, including NERC, including reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense, and costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the AEPOTC Indemnified Person, arising in connection with this Agreement, except to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of AEPOTC or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.1.3. AEPOTC shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless Seven Cowboy, its Affiliates, and its or their directors, managers, officers, employees, and agents (each a Seven Cowboy Indemnified Person) for any personal injuries suffered by third parties or damage to a third partys tangible property, reasonable attorney fees and other costs and expenses of defense, and costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the Seven Cowboy Indemnified Person, arising in connection with the performance by AEPOTC of its obligations under this Agreement and to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the negligence, gross negligence or willful misconduct of AEPOTC or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors.
9.2. Procedure. Each AEPOTC Indemnified Person or Seven Cowboy Indemnified Person (individually, Indemnified Person), as applicable, must provide prompt notice of any claim f or which it seeks indemnity under this provision and cooperate in def ense of each such claim. Without the consent of the applicable Indemnified Person, a Party may not settle any such claim for any relief (other than monetary damages) or any claim in the nature of regulatory or similar legal enforcement action by a Governmental Authority. 9.3. Cumulative Rights. The rights and remedies provided to an Indemnified Person under this Article 9 are cumulative with any other right such Person has or may hereafter acquire under Applicable Law and any rights or remedies such Person has may be asserted completely against a Party without regard to any rights or remedies the Indemnified Person may have against any other Person. 10. CONFIDENTIALITY 10.1. Confidential Information. For purposes of this Agreement, a Partys Confidential Information consists of information possessed by that Party which is confidential and commercially valuable and which is specifically identified to the other Party as confidential. Information is Confidential Information only if it is clearly designated or marked in writing as confidential on the face of the document, or, if the information is conveyed orally or by inspection, if the Party providing the inf ormation (the Disclosing Party) informs, in writing, the Party receiving the information (the Receiving Party) that the information is confidential. Confidential Information will not include any information which the Receiving Party can demonstrate (a) has become available to the public through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was previously known by the Receiving Party without any obligation to hold it in confidence; (c) was received on a non- confidential basis from a third party free to disclose such information without restriction; or (d) was independently developed by the Receiving Party without the use of Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party. 10.2. Receipt and Disclosure. For purposes of this Agreement, a Party will be deemed to have received Confidential Information of the other Party if such Confidential Information is by any means disclosed or delivered to the Receiving Party or any of its or its Affiliates equity owners, directors, managers, officers, employees, advisors, attorneys, agents, or prospective or actual lenders or investors (its Representatives). Each Party hereto agrees that it shall hold in strict conf idence and shall not disclose or use any Confidential Information belonging to the other Party hereto for the period ending eighteen (18) months after the expiration of the Term or earlier termination of this Agreement. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to its Representatives for purposes of meeting its obligations and exercising its rights hereunder, provided that the Representatives shall be informed of the confidentiality obligations provided herein. Each Party agrees to be responsible for any breach of the confidentiality obligations under this Agreement by its Representatives. 10.3. Required Disclosures. If a Party is required pursuant to Applicable Law or otherwise becomes legally compelled to disclose any of the Confidential Information or the fact that the Confidential Information has been made available to it, such Party shall (unless prohibited by Applicable Law from doing so) promptly notify the Disclosing Party in
order that the Disclosing Party may seek a protective order or such other remedy as the Disclosing Party may consider appropriate in the circumstances. In any event, the compelled Party may disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information which such Party is legally required to disclose in the judgment of the Partys legal counsel without any liability to the Disclosing Party hereunder and such disclosure shall not be a breach of this Article 10. 10.4. Return or Destruction. The Receiving Party, upon written request from the Disclosing Party, shall promptly return or destroy all Conf idential Inf ormation in its possession and the Receiving Party shall destroy its Evaluation Materials. If requested by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall provide the Disclosing Party with a certif ication that all Conf idential Inf ormation and Evaluation Materials have either been returned or destroyed, as applicable. The return or destruction of the Confidential Information shall not extinguish any rights or obligations under this Agreement with respect to the Confidential Information. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party shall not be required to purge any historical backup media and may retain one or more copies of the Conf idential Inf ormation solely f or archival purposes and as required by Applicable Law. 10.5. Survival. The provisions of this Article 10 shall survive a termination of this Agreement. 11. GENERAL PROVISIONS 11.1. Notices. Any notice that is required or permitted under this Agreement may be given by personal delivery to the Party entitled thereto, by e-mail (with confirmation of receipt), by any courier service which guarantees overnight, receipted delivery, or by U.S. Certified or Registered Mail, return receipt requested, addressed to the Party entitled thereto, at the following addresses. Any Party may change its address or email for notice by written notice to the other Parties in accordance with this Section. Such change will not necessitate a filing under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act. 11.2. Interest on Overdue Amounts. Any amount due to a Party under this Agreement will accrue interest daily from the deadline for payment thereof until paid at the Default Rate. 11.3. Amendment. This Agreement may not be amended except by a written instrument executed by the Parties hereto. 11.4. Assignment. Neither Party may assign any of its rights or delegate any of its duties under this Agreement to any Person without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent will not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, or delayed. Notwithstanding the f oregoing, no consent will be required if the assignee is an Af f iliate of the assigning Party, provided such Affiliate assumes all of the assigning Partys obligations and liabilities under this Agreement and agrees to be bound by this Agreement. 11.5. Merger and Integration; Binding on Successors; No Third Party Beneficiaries. This Agreement sets out the entire understanding of the Parties with respect to the matters it purports to cover and supersedes all prior communications, agreements, and understandings, whether written or oral, concerning such matters. Neither Party will be liable or bound to the other Party in any manner by any warranties, representations, or covenants with respect to the matters this Agreement purports to cover other than those set forth in or incorporated into this Agreement. The terms and conditions of this Agreement will inure to the benefit of and be binding upon the respective successors and permitted assigns of the Parties. Nothing in this Agreement, express or implied, is intended to confer upon any third party any rights, remedies, obligations, or liabilities under or by reason of this Agreement, except as expressly provided in this Agreement. Nothing in this Agreement is intended to modify the GIA, nor shall this Agreement supersede the GIA. In the event of a conf lict between the terms of the GIA and the terms of this Agreement, the terms of this Agreement shall control. 11.6. Forbearance and Waiver. Except where a specific time period is provided hereunder for the exercise of a right or remedy, any Partys forbearance in the exercise or enforcement of any right or remedy under this Agreement will not constitute a waiver thereof, and a waiver under one circumstance will not constitute a waiver under any other circumstance.
11.7. Partial Invalidity. Any invalidity, illegality, or unenforceability of any provision of this Agreement in any jurisdiction will not invalidate or render illegal or unenforceable the remaining provisions hereof in such jurisdiction and will not invalidate or render illegal or unenforceable such provision in any other jurisdiction. 11.8. Survival. Any provision specifically designated in this Agreement to survive the termination hereof and (unless otherwise expressly provided) any other provision which, by its nature, necessarily may become performable by a Party after termination of this Agreement will survive termination of this Agreement. 11.9. Governing Law; Venue; Waiver of Jury Trial. 11.9.1. Except as to matters preempted by the Constitution and statutes of the United States of America or regulations promulgated thereunder, this Agreement will be governed by, interpreted, construed, and enforced in accordance with the laws of the State of Oklahoma without regard to any conflict-of-law provisions that may refer to the laws of any other jurisdiction. After giving effect to the preceding sentence, this Agreement is subject to all valid applicable federal, state, and local laws, ordinances, rules, and regulations of duly constituted regulatory authorities having jurisdiction. 11.9.2. The Parties hereby irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of any state or f ederal court sitting in the State of Oklahoma any action or proceeding arising out of, or relating to, this Agreement, and irrevocably agree that all claims in respect of such action or proceeding may be heard and determined in any such court. 11.9.3. THE PARTIES EACH HEREBY IRREVOCABLY WAIVE ALL RIGHT TO TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION, PROCEEDING OR COUNTERCLAIM ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO ANY OF THE TRANSACTIONS CONTEMPLATED HEREBY. EACH PARTY FURTHER WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO CONSOLIDATE ANY ACTION IN WHICH A JURY TRIAL HAS BEEN WAIVED WITH ANY OTHER ACTION IN WHICH A JURY TRIAL CANNOT BE OR HAS NOT BEEN WAIVED. 11.10. Multiple Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed by the Parties in multiple original counterparts, and each such counterpart will constitute an original hereof.

FORMULA RATE FOR OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE
A. General
The formula rate contained in this Exhibit B applies when AEPOTC performs operation and maintenance (O&M) activities for non-AEPOTC parties. AEPOTC will recover costs for the performance of O&M through invoices that reflect the costs AEPOTC incurred in the following six categories, namely: (1) materials; (2) labor; (3) equipment; (4) outside services; (5) engineering and administration; and (6) taxes.
AEPOTC charges its costs for O&M activities on behalf of others to special work orders that accumulate the costs to be billed. As a result of these accounting procedures, the charges billed to non-AEPOTC parties are not reflected in AEPOTCs transmission, operation, maintenance, or plant accounts.
The types of costs that AEPOTC incurs and bills are the types of costs that would be assignable to the following FERC Uniform System of Accounts if they were incurred in connection with AEPOTCs own property:
Operation and Maintenance - Transmission Operation and Maintenance Expenses
560 - Operation Supervision and Engineering 562 - Station Expenses 563 - Overhead Line Expenses 566 - Miscellaneous Transmission Expenses 568 - Maintenance Supervision and Engineering 569 - Maintenance of Structures 570 - Maintenance of Station Equipment 571 - Maintenance of Overhead Lines
Construction - Transmission Plant Costs
352 - Structures and Improvements 353 - Station Equipment 397 - Communications Equipment 108 - Accumulated Provision for Depreciation
All Activities - Administrative, General and Other Expenses
920 - Administrative and General Salaries 408 - Taxes Other Than Income Taxes
The charges billed for O&M in each of the previously identified six categories are discussed in order below.
#2846723v1 1. Materials
Materials charges are made in four sub-categories: (1) direct material costs (DM), which may be (a) delivered direct from vendors to the job site (VDM), or (b) issued from company stores (SDM); (2) purchasing expenses (PE); (3) stores expenses (SE); and (4) exempt minor materials (EM). The latter three costs are charged using material loading rates described below.
DM costs are vendor invoiced charges for items, other than exempt minor materials, which are used f or maintenance. PE are material overhead costs incurred in selecting and ordering materials. SE are the costs of perf orming the stores function. EM are low cost expendable materials, supplies, and hand tools used in transmission operation and maintenance.
VDM are charged at cost, plus a purchasing loading rate (plr) of 1%, up to a maximum of $150 per invoice. SDM are charged at cost, plus a combined stores/purchasing loading rate (slr) and an EM loading rate (mlr).
Projected annual SE and EM costs are divided by projected annual costs of stores issued materials (SDM + EM) to determine projected SE and EM loading rates. The rates are reviewed monthly and adjusted as required to clear current year SE and EM costs to the accounts charged with the materials issued.
In symbolic format, the charges for materials are calculated as follows:
M = DM + [VDM x (plr), up to $150/bill] + SDM x (1 + (mlr)) x (slr)
2. Labor
Labor is charged to maintenance work orders in three parts - direct labor (DL), f ringe labor costs (FL), and miscellaneous out-of-pocket employee expenses (ME). DL charges reflect the actual work hours (whr) and basic hourly rates of pay (hrp) for the personnel that are directly involved; i.e., DL = (whr) x (hrp). FL costs for vacation, holiday, sick leave, and other paid time away, plus payroll taxes, insurance, workers compensation, pension, savings plan expenses, etc. are recovered through labor loading rates (llr) that are developed by dividing FL earned payroll. The llr are reviewed monthly and adjusted, as needed, to clear FL costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the charges for labor are calculated as follows:
L = DL + FL + ME = DL x (1 + llr) + ME
3. Equipment
Equipment (E), primarily vehicles, used in the performance of maintenance are charged based on actual hours of usage (aeu) and hourly equipment cost rates (ecr). Cost of purchasing, leasing, and operating equipment, by equipment class, are collected in clearing accounts and divided by total hours of usage by class to develop the E cost rates. E cost rates are reviewed quarterly and adjusted, as needed, to clear the cost of E.
#2846723v1 In symbolic format, E charges are calculated as follows:
E = (aeu) x (ecr)
4. Outside Services
The actual amount of invoices received from vendors for restorative and other maintenance services (S) performed by third parties for AEPOTC are charged in maintenance billings by AEPOTC.
5. Engineering and Administration
Engineering and administrative overhead loading rates are used to allocate engineering, supervision, and administrative overhead costs not assigned to specific project work orders. AEPOTC uses separate loading rates for American Electric Power Service Corporation (AEPSC) engineering (SCEt&d) and construction overhead costs (CCO).
As the description of Construction Overhead Procedure in Section B below shows, the CCO and SCEt&d loading rates (cclr and sclrt&d, respectively) are derived in the normal course of business for the purpose of capturing the portions of AEPSC engineering and operating company construction overhead costs which are incurred in connection with transmission and distribution (T&D) plan construction. The cclr and sclrt&d are reviewed monthly and updated, as needed, to clear the respective engineering and administrative overhead costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the engineering and administration overhead costs (O) are calculated as follows:
O = CCO + SCEt&d
Where CCO = (M + L + E + S) x cclr
and SCEt&d = (M + L + E + S + CCO) x sclrt&d
#2846723v1 6. Taxes
The total taxes charged to Seven Cowboy will be the sum of receipts (RT) and other taxes incurred (OT).
i.e.: T = RT + OT
B. Summary of Charges
The total O&M charges under this Agreement in symbolic form are:
O&M = M + L + E + S + O + T
Where M, L, E, S, O, and T are calculated as explained in Sections A.1 through A.6 above, respectively.
General Description of Construction Overhead Procedure:
1A. Engineering and Supervision (AEPSC)
(a) Overheads Engineering, Technical and Drafting Services are engineering services performed by AEPSC.
(b) In accordance with provisions of a service agreement between AEPSC and AEPOTC, salaries, expenses and overheads of AEPSC personnel directly relating to construction activities are collected by means of a work order system and billed to AEPOTC as:
(1) Identif iable costs, generally relating to major construction projects, f or which timekeeping and other specific cost identification is economically feasible, and
(2) Non-identifiable costs, generally relating to numerous small construction projects, for which timekeeping and other specific cost identification are not economically feasible.
(c) Charges billed by AEPSC as (b)(1) above are charged directly by respondent to the applicable specific construction projects. Charges billed by AEPSC as (b)(2) above are allocated to all applicable construction projects proportionate to the direct costs charged to such projects.
(d) A uniform rate is applied to all subject construction expenditures.
#2846723v1 1B. Company Construction Overheads AEPOTC Engineering Costs
(a) Charges representing cost of AEPOTC's engineering supervision and related drafting and technical work.
(b) On basis of time and work studies.
(c) Spread to accounts in proportion to dollar value on construction for those classes of construction accounts to which these overheads are considered to be applicable.
(d) For each class of overheads the same percentage is used for all types of construction.
1C. Company Construction Overheads - Administrative and General Expenses
(a) Proportion of Administrative and General Expenses representing salaries and expenses of general office and managerial employees applicable to construction. (b) Partly on basis of time and work studies. (c) Spread to accounts in proportion to dollar value of construction for those classes of construction accounts to which these overheads are considered to be applicable. (d) For each class of overheads the same percentage is used for all types of construction.

PRELIMINARY DEVELOPMENT AGREEMENT
This Preliminary Development Agreement (the Agreement) is entered into as of the date of last signature below (the Execution Date) between AEP Oklahoma Transmission Company, Inc., an Oklahoma corporation (AEPOTC) and Crooked Creek Solar, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Generator). AEPOTC and Generator may be referred to individually as a Party and collectively as the Parties.
RECITALS
A. Generator is in the process of developing certain generation assets in McCurtain County, Oklahoma with a proposed capacity of 155 MW (the Plant).
B. The Southwest Power Pool (SPP) is conducting an Interconnection Facilities Study (Facilities Study) in response to Generators Generation Interconnection Request #GEN- 2021-063 to SPP to interconnect the Plant. It is anticipated the Plant would be interconnected to the AEPOTC system. The completed Facilities Study will identify certain interconnection facilities necessary or appropriate to enable interconnection service to Generator for the Plant (the Interconnection Facilities).
C. The Parties anticipate entering into an SPP standard Generation Interconnection Agreement (the GIA) and possibly an Interim Generation Interconnection Agreement (the Interim GIA) in advance of the GIA that will, among other things, address the engineering, procurement, and construction of the Interconnection Facilities.
D. Generator has requested that AEPOTC perform certain preliminary planning, engineering, design, and procurement activities related to the proposed interconnection prior to the execution of the GIA or Interim GIA by the Parties. AEPOTC is willing to do so on the terms and conditions set out in this Agreement.
AGREEMENTS
NOW, THEREFORE, the Parties hereby agree as follows:
1. DEFINITIONS; RULES OF CONSTRUCTION
1.1. Definitions. As used in this Agreement, terms defined in Exhibit 1.1 have the meanings set forth therein.
1.2. Rules of Construction. Unless the context of this Agreement requires otherwise, the plural includes the singular, and the singular includes the plural. The words include, includes and including are not limiting and have the inclusive meaning of including without limitation. The words hereof, herein, hereby, hereunder and other similar terms of this Agreement refer to this Agreement as a whole and not exclusively to any particular provision of this Agreement. All pronouns and any variations thereof will be deemed to refer to masculine, feminine, or neuter, singular, or plural, as the identity of the Person or Persons may require. Unless otherwise expressly provided, any agreement, instrument, or Applicable Law defined or referred to herein means such agreement or instrument or Applicable Law as from time to time amended,
Preliminary Development Agreement, GEN-2021-063 Page 1
modified, or supplemented, including (in the case of agreements or instruments) by waiver or consent and (in the case of Applicable Law) by succession of comparable successor law and includes (in the case of agreements or instruments) references to all attachments thereto and instruments incorporated therein. A reference to a Party includes its successors and permitted assigns. This Agreement is the result of negotiations between, and has been reviewed by, the Parties, and their respective counsel have had the opportunity to review this Agreement. Accordingly, this Agreement shall be deemed to be the product of all Parties hereto, and no ambiguity shall be construed in favor of or against any Party.
2. EFFECTIVE DATE; COMMENCEMENT DATE; TERMINATION
2.1. Commencement of Work. AEPOTC shall become obligated to commence the Work hereunder when both the Effective Date has occurred in accordance with Section 2.2 and the Commencement Date has occurred in accordance with Section 2.3.
2.2. Effective Date. AEPOTC shall file this Agreement with FERC, and Generator agrees to cooperate with AEPOTC and provide reasonable assistance to AEPOTC in such filing and proceedings related thereto. This Agreement shall become effective on the date specified by FERC (Effective Date). However, if FERC or any other Governmental Authority suspends this Agreement or any part thereof, institutes an investigation or proceeding with respect to this Agreement or any other agreement referred to or contemplated by this Agreement, or imposes any conditions, limitation or qualifications which individually or in the aggregate are determined by AEPOTC or Generator to be adverse to it, then either AEPOTC or Generator may terminate this Agreement upon written notice to the other Party.
2.3. Commencement Date. The commencement date shall be the date on which each of the following events shall have occurred or been waived by the Parties (Commencement Date):
2.3.1. Receipt by both Parties of all necessary Governmental Approvals (in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to each of the Parties) in addition to the Governmental Approval specified in Section 2.2 hereof.
2.3.2. AEPOTCs receipt of any Security described in Section 4.2 and any replacements or increases thereto.
If, at the request of Generator, AEPOTC waives a condition specified in this Section 2.3 so that Work can proceed, AEPOTC will be entitled to reimbursement of costs pursuant to this Agreement as if the Work had been performed only after satisfaction of the waived condition.
2.4. Events of Termination. This Agreement may be terminated by the Parties as follows:
2.4.1. This Agreement may be terminated by mutual written agreement of the Parties.
2.4.2. This Agreement will terminate upon execution of the GIA or Interim GIA, if applicable, by the Parties, and any further measures with respect to the Work will be undertaken pursuant to the GIA or Interim GIA.
Preliminary Development Agreement GEN-2021-063 Page 2
2.4.3. Generator may terminate this Agreement for convenience on ten (10) days advance written notice to the other Party.
2.4.4. Either Party may terminate this Agreement as provided in Sections 2.2, 5.1, and 6.2.
2.4.5. AEPOTC may terminate this Agreement on written notice to Generator if Generator has not executed a GIA or Interim GIA for the Plant with AEPOTC withing twelve (12) months of the Execution Date.
2.4.6. Either Party may terminate this Agreement if any Governmental Authority denies approval of any necessary or appropriate approvals for the Work or the Plant, or if any Governmental Authority shall have issued an order, decree, ruling, or other action restraining, enjoining, or otherwise prohibiting such Partys performance of this Agreement or its contemplated ownership or operation of the Plant or Interconnection Facilities.
2.5. Regulatory Approval of Termination. Any termination of this Agreement provided for herein shall be subject to any necessary approval by FERC or any other Governmental Authority, as applicable.
2.6. Survival of Rights; Merger into GIA.
2.6.1. Subject to Section 2.6.2, termination of this Agreement shall not relieve the Parties of obligations that by their nature should survive such termination, including, without limitation, payment obligations, remedies, indemnification obligations, confidentiality and any provisions of this Agreement that explicitly provide for survival after termination.
2.6.2. If the Parties execute a GIA or Interim GIA, then, except as otherwise provided in the GIA or Interim GIA, all of the rights and obligations of the Parties with respect to the Work will be merged into and controlled exclusively by the GIA or Interim GIA, and the provisions of this Agreement will have no continuing force or effect; provided, however, that any amount payable hereunder that does not become part of the amounts payable under the GIA or Interim GIA will continue to be subject to invoicing and payment (including application of the Security) under this Agreement.
2.7. Termination Costs. If a Party elects to terminate this Agreement pursuant to Article 2.4 above (other than pursuant to Section 2.4.2), Generator shall pay all costs incurred by AEPOTC for the Work performed hereunder (including any cancellation costs relating to orders or contracts for materials and equipment procured hereunder), as of the date the non-terminating Party receives notice of the termination (Termination Date). In the event of termination by any Party, AEPOTC shall use commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate the costs, damages and charges arising as a consequence of
Preliminary Development Agreement GEN-2021-063 Page 3
termination. Upon termination of this Agreement (other than pursuant to Section 2.4.2), unless otherwise ordered or approved by FERC:
2.7.1. AEPOTC shall, to the extent possible, and with Generator's authorization cancel any pending orders of, or return, any materials or equipment procured hereunder; provided that in the event Generator elects not to authorize such cancellation, Generator shall assume all payment obligations with respect to such materials, equipment, and contracts, and AEPOTC shall deliver such material and equipment, and, if necessary, assign such orders, to Generator as soon as practicable, at Generator's expense. If Generator does not provide its authorization to cancel pending orders within three (3) Business Days of the termination date, the Generator shall be deemed to have authorized cancellation of all pending orders and return of materials and equipment.
2.7.2. Except as specifically provided in this Section, Generator shall be responsible for all costs incurred in association with the Work incurred up to the date of the Termination Date, including any cancellation costs relating to orders or contracts for materials and equipment, and other expenses for which AEPOTC has incurred expenses and has not been reimbursed by Generator.
2.7.3. If Generator chooses not to accept delivery of materials or, equipment procured hereunder Generator shall be responsible for all costs associated with procuring such materials and equipment to the extent that AEPOTC determines that it would not able to utilize such materials, equipment or facilities or that it would not be able to recover the costs for such materials, equipment or facilities in its rates. To the extent that Generator has already paid AEPOTC for any or all such costs of materials or equipment not taken by Generator and AEPOTC is able to utilize such materials or equipment and recover their costs in rates, AEPOTC shall refund such amounts to Generator, less any costs including penalties incurred by AEPOTC to cancel any pending orders or return such materials or equipment. Such refund, if any, will occur upon final reconciliation of project costs pursuant to Section 4.1.3.
3. PRELIMINARY DEVELOPMENT WORK
3.1. Scope of Work. AEPOTC will undertake, directly or through its affiliates or contractors (or any combination thereof), the performance of the work described in Schedule 3.1 and any attachments referenced therein (the Work).
3.2. Modification of the Work. Because the Work has been specified in this Agreement prior to the completion of the Facilities Study relating to the Plant, the Parties acknowledge that the specification of the Work and the estimates of its cost set out in this Agreement are not binding on AEPOTC and that AEPOTC may modify Schedule 3.1 to reflect the results of the Facilities Study on written notice to Generator.
3.3. Generators Technical Information. Generator will provide relevant information to AEPOTC concerning the Plant and the Work as requested by AEPOTC from time to time. Generator represents that any technical or engineering information, reports, drawings, data,
Preliminary Development Agreement GEN-2021-063 Page 4
specifications, analyses, and other similar materials previously or hereafter provided to AEPOTC or to SPP by Generator or Generators contractors or consultants in connection with the Plant or the Work has been and will be prepared in accordance with Good Utility Practice and that Generator is not aware of any reason to distrust the accuracy and completeness of such information and materials.
3.4. Disclaimer of Warranty. AEPOTC will perform the Work consistent with Applicable Law, applicable Governmental Approvals, and Good Utility Practice. Except for the foregoing, AEPOTC HEREBY DISCLAIMS ALL EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES, INCLUDING WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR GOOD AND WORKMANLIKE PERFORMANCE. THE FOREGOING STANDARDS FOR PERFORMANCE OF THIS AGREEMENT WILL BE MERGED INTO THE GIA AS PROVIDED IN SECTION 2.6, AND THE ONLY WARRANTIES WITH RESPECT TO THE WORK WILL THEREUPON BE THOSE PROVIDED BY THE GIA.
3.5. Progress Reports. From time to time as reasonably determined by AEPOTC, AEPOTC will report to Generator concerning the progress of the Work.
4. COSTS
4.1. Responsibility for Costs; Initial Payments; Final Reconciliation.
4.1.1. Generator will bear all costs of the Work (including any modifications thereto) except to the extent that the Parties agree otherwise in the GIA or Interim GIA. Costs to be borne by the Generator for the Work under this Agreement will include all costs, charges, and expenses incurred by AEPOTC in connection with the Work, including the costs of materials, equipment, and supplies from third parties, the costs of materials and equipment withdrawn from AEPOTCs internal inventories (or those of its affiliates), transportation and storage costs, internal payroll and payroll loading factors, travel expenses, overhead factors, other internal costs, the costs to acquire land rights, third party expenses, sales and use taxes, and fees and costs for Governmental Approvals.
4.1.2. Generator shall make two payments to AEPOTC as follows:
(a) Within thirty (30) Business Days after this Agreement is filed at FERC, AEPOTC shall issue an invoice to Generator for $500,000 for the engineering and design portion of the Work described in Schedule 3.1. Generator shall make the payment to AEPOTC according to the due date on the invoice. AEPOTC shall not be obligated to commence any portion of the engineering and design work until it receives the foregoing payment.
(b) Within seven months after the Execution Date, AEPOTC shall issue an invoice to Generator for $1,500,000 for the procurement portion of the Work described in Schedule 3.1. Generator shall make the payment to AEPOTC according to the due date on the
Preliminary Development Agreement GEN-2021-063 Page 5
invoice. AEPOTC shall not be obligated to commence any procurement activities until it receives the foregoing payment.
4.1.3. Upon completion of the Work, AEPOTC shall submit an invoice to Generator for the total costs of the Work under this Agreement, and Generator shall pay such costs to the extent they exceed the initial payment of $2,000,000. Such invoice shall include any income tax gross-up that may result under Applicable Law if income tax is payable by AEPOTC with respect to payments by Generator to AEPOTC, and such invoice will be payable in full, without offset, abatement, or reduction for any reason, within thirty (30) Calendar Days of the date of invoice. If Generator in good faith disputes any portion of an invoice, Generator will (i) explain the basis for the dispute in writing to AEPOTC within fifteen (15) Calendar Days of the date of the invoice and (ii) without prejudice to its claim for refund of any disputed amount, pay the entire portion of the invoiced amount on or before the due date stated on the invoice.
4.2. Information Concerning Costs. On reasonable advance written notice, Generator will have the right to examine the pertinent records of AEPOTC as reasonably necessary to verify that costs invoiced pursuant to this Agreement were incurred in accordance with this Agreement. Any such examination will be conducted during regular business hours at the AEPOTC offices or remotely if so specified by AEPOTC. Generator will not have the right to examine the records pertaining to a particular invoice more than once or to examine the records pertaining to an invoice unless written notice of the examination is given within twenty-four (24) months of the date of such invoice. AEPOTC shall not be required to provide information that (a) is subject to confidentiality restrictions of third parties; (b) protected by attorney-client privilege; or (c) identifies components of internal charges of AEPOTC or its affiliates. Information obtained by Generator from AEPOTC pursuant to this section shall be considered Confidential Information of AEPOTC subject to the confidentiality provisions of Article 8 hereof regardless of whether such information is marked as confidential.
4.3. Survival. Subject to Section 2.6.2, the provisions of this Article 4 shall survive termination of this Agreement.
5. FORCE MAJEURE
5.1. Effect of Force Majeure. In the event that either Party is rendered unable by reason of an event of Force Majeure occurring or arising without the fault or negligence of such Party to perform, wholly or in part, any obligation or commitment set forth in this Agreement, then the obligations of such Party (except for the obligation to pay sums of money owing hereunder for periods prior to the event of Force Majeure) shall be suspended to the extent of such Force Majeure condition, and such Party shall not be deemed to be in default of this Agreement, for the period of such Force Majeure condition. A Party affected by an event of Force Majeure shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate the effects of such Force Majeure. A Partys lack of funds shall not be an event of Force Majeure. Either Party will have the right to terminate this Agreement if a Force Majeure event prevents performance for more than ninety (90) consecutive days.
Preliminary Development Agreement GEN-2021-063 Page 6
5.2. Notification. In the event of the occurrence of an event of Force Majeure, which prevents a Party from performing its obligations hereunder, such Party shall notify the other Party of such Force Majeure, in writing or by telephone as soon as reasonably possible after the determination that event of Force Majeure has occurred, but in any event within seven (7) Calendar Days thereafter (telephone notices to be confirmed in writing as soon as reasonably possible).
5.3. Labor Disputes. Neither Party will be required by this Agreement to settle any strike, walkout, lockout, or other labor dispute on terms which, in the sole judgment of the Party involved in the dispute, are contrary to its interest, it being understood that the settlement of strikes, walkouts, lockouts, or other labor disputes will be at the sole discretion of the Party having the difficulty.
6. DEFAULT; REMEDIES
6.1. Events of Default. An Event of Default will exist:
6.1.1. As to Generator upon Generators failure to promptly pay any amount due hereunder (including a failure by Generator to provide Security when required or a failure to increase, replenish or replace Security as required by Section 4.2.1) within ten (10) Calendar Days following written notice of delinquency;
6.1.2. As to a Party if that Party fails to commence the cure of its breach of any other obligation under this Agreement within sixty (60) Calendar Days following written notification of such breach; or
6.1.3. As to a Party if it becomes Insolvent.
6.2. Termination. If an Event of Default in any material respect occurs as to a Party, the other Party will have the right to terminate this Agreement on written notice to the defaulting Party.
6.3. Other remedies.
6.3.1.
